WEBVTT

00:05.972 --> 00:09.008
♪ ♪

00:10.377 --> 00:11.911
John Wilson:
<i>Hey, New York.</i>

00:13.947 --> 00:15.882
<i>Every time I throw</i>
<i>something out,</i>

00:15.949 --> 00:18.451
<i>It feels like I'm getting</i>
<i>away with something.</i>

00:19.719 --> 00:21.755
<i>On Tuesday and Friday</i>
<i>every week,</i>

00:21.821 --> 00:24.591
<i>all the evidence of</i>
<i>my shameful lifestyle</i>

00:24.657 --> 00:26.593
<i>is removed</i>
<i>without any question.</i>

00:26.659 --> 00:29.195
<i>And I never have to think</i>
<i>about it ever again.</i>

00:30.830 --> 00:32.565
<i>It's amazing to think</i>
<i>that it's this easy</i>

00:32.632 --> 00:34.834
<i>to get rid of something.</i>

00:34.901 --> 00:36.236
<i>But there's always</i>
<i>going to be some stuff</i>

00:36.302 --> 00:38.838
<i>that you're never quite</i>
<i>sure how to throw away.</i>

00:40.340 --> 00:42.475
<i>I have a big box</i>
<i>of used batteries</i>

00:42.542 --> 00:45.678
<i>that I keep</i>
<i>in my apartment.</i>
(clears throat)

00:45.745 --> 00:48.615
<i>They're, uh--</i>
<i>I think they're all dead,</i>

00:48.681 --> 00:50.784
<i>but I'm afraid to throw</i>
<i>them into the normal trash</i>

00:50.850 --> 00:53.353
<i>for reasons I don't</i>
<i>quite understand.</i>

00:54.587 --> 00:56.222
<i>I thought I was</i>
<i>the only one,</i>

00:56.289 --> 00:58.658
<i>but when I--</i>
<i>but when I talked</i>
<i>to my neighbors,</i>

00:58.725 --> 01:00.660
<i>it seems like they had</i>
<i>the same problem as me.</i>

01:00.727 --> 01:04.497
-This is my bag for...
-(bag crinkling)

01:04.564 --> 01:06.733
things like that, I guess.

01:06.800 --> 01:08.768
Wilson:
What else is in there?

01:08.835 --> 01:10.637
I don't know what to
do with them, either.

01:10.703 --> 01:12.972
You're stuck with them,
and then they dry up,

01:13.039 --> 01:15.108
and you can't
use them at all.

01:15.175 --> 01:17.076
Wilson:
<i>There seemed to be a lot</i>
<i>of mixed messaging</i>

01:17.143 --> 01:19.612
<i>about how to get rid</i>
<i>of stuff like this and,</i>

01:19.679 --> 01:22.949
<i>and that causes some people to</i>
<i>hold on to things indefinitely.</i>

01:23.016 --> 01:25.985
And so if I just put
it out in the trash,

01:26.052 --> 01:28.988
I feel like I'm not
being a good citizen.

01:29.055 --> 01:30.723
I really do.

01:30.790 --> 01:33.193
Wilson:
<i>Disposing of things</i>
<i>correctly can make you feel</i>

01:33.259 --> 01:35.829
<i>like you're doing</i>
<i>the Lord's work.</i>

01:35.895 --> 01:39.732
<i>So instead of holding onto this</i>
<i>stuff longer than you have to,</i>

01:39.799 --> 01:41.801
<i>stick with me,</i>
<i>and I'll show you</i>

01:41.868 --> 01:43.636
<i>how to get your life in order</i>

01:43.703 --> 01:45.638
<i>and finally figure out</i>
<i>the right way</i>

01:45.705 --> 01:48.241
<i>to get rid of</i>
<i>all your batteries.</i>

01:49.108 --> 01:50.143
(clears throat)

01:53.246 --> 01:55.215
<i>The first place</i>
<i>you should try is the</i>

01:55.281 --> 01:58.651
<i>hazardous waste drop-off</i>
<i>site that the city has set up</i>

01:58.718 --> 02:02.255
<i>right under</i>
<i>the Manhattan Bridge</i>
<i>on the Lower East Side.</i>

02:02.322 --> 02:04.524
<i>But when you get there,</i>
<i>it seems like</i>

02:04.591 --> 02:06.359
<i>it's temporarily closed,</i>

02:06.426 --> 02:08.328
<i>and they don't</i>
<i>give any indication</i>

02:08.394 --> 02:10.730
<i>as to when</i>
<i>it's going to reopen.</i>

02:10.797 --> 02:14.534
<i>So, you're gonna have to</i>
<i>figure something else out.</i>

02:14.601 --> 02:15.802
♪ ♪

02:15.869 --> 02:18.004
<i>Thankfully, when you're walking</i>
<i>around your neighborhood,</i>

02:18.071 --> 02:19.405
<i>you actually stumble across,</i>

02:19.472 --> 02:22.141
<i>uh, an electronic waste event,</i>

02:22.208 --> 02:24.911
<i>where you're supposed to</i>
<i>throw out stuff like this.</i>

02:24.978 --> 02:28.915
<i>But when you ask them</i>
<i>if they can, uh,</i>
<i>take your batteries,</i>

02:28.982 --> 02:31.384
<i>uh, you get some</i>
<i>disappointing news.</i>

02:34.487 --> 02:35.955
-Wilson: You don't
take batteries?
-No.

02:36.022 --> 02:37.991
So, we used to have
a warehouse in Brooklyn,

02:38.057 --> 02:40.026
and then the landlord
raised the rent.

02:40.093 --> 02:43.062
And so now, if you look behind
you, we've got a truck there.

02:43.129 --> 02:44.898
Wilson:
So, where would I throw
out my batteries?

02:44.964 --> 02:47.467
Best Buy, Staples, Home Depot,

02:47.534 --> 02:48.968
Lowe's, or IKEA will take them.

02:49.035 --> 02:50.737
-Wilson: Oh, really?
-Yeah.

02:50.803 --> 02:54.440
Wilson:
<i>So, take your batteries</i>
<i>down to the subway station</i>

02:54.507 --> 02:57.110
<i>and bring them all</i>
<i>the way to the place</i>

02:57.176 --> 02:59.145
<i>he was talking about.</i>

02:59.212 --> 03:02.682
<i>The first place,</i>
<i>uh, didn't, um...</i>

03:02.749 --> 03:05.451
<i>it didn't seem</i>
<i>open right now. So,</i>

03:05.518 --> 03:09.289
<i>get back on the subway</i>
<i>and take your batteries</i>

03:09.355 --> 03:12.058
<i>all the way to the next</i>
<i>place that he mentioned.</i>

03:13.159 --> 03:14.494
<i>But when you get in there,</i>

03:14.561 --> 03:16.763
<i>you have a tough time</i>
<i>finding the receptacle</i>

03:16.829 --> 03:18.331
<i>that he was talking about.</i>

03:18.398 --> 03:21.000
<i>And you have</i>
<i>an even harder time,</i>

03:21.067 --> 03:22.602
<i>uh, finding an employee.</i>

03:22.669 --> 03:24.103
Excuse me, do you work here?

03:24.170 --> 03:25.805
-No.
-Wilson: Oh, sorry.

03:25.872 --> 03:27.473
-You don't work here,
do you?
-No, I don't.

03:27.540 --> 03:29.976
-Wilson: Okay.
It's the orange shirt.
-(laughs)

03:30.043 --> 03:32.445
<i>And after searching</i>
<i>for a while,</i>

03:32.512 --> 03:35.315
<i>you start to wonder why</i>
<i>they make this so hard.</i>

03:35.381 --> 03:36.749
♪ ♪

03:36.816 --> 03:38.051
<i>If you're gonna be</i>
<i>buying batteries</i>

03:38.117 --> 03:39.586
<i>for the rest of your life,</i>

03:39.652 --> 03:41.154
<i>are you going to</i>
<i>have to come back</i>

03:41.220 --> 03:43.289
<i>to this godforsaken place</i>

03:43.356 --> 03:45.892
<i>every sing-- every time</i>
<i>your box fills up?</i>

03:47.193 --> 03:49.562
<i>And you wish you could</i>
<i>just get rid of these</i>

03:49.629 --> 03:52.565
<i>the same way that</i>
<i>you do everything else.</i>

03:52.632 --> 03:54.834
<i>But, for some reason,</i>

03:54.901 --> 03:57.437
<i>that's not an option.</i>

03:57.503 --> 04:00.306
<i>Even if you were to</i>
<i>recycle these things,</i>

04:00.373 --> 04:03.142
<i>you're not even sure if that</i>
<i>would make you feel better.</i>

04:04.310 --> 04:06.212
<i>You separate all</i>
<i>your cans and stuff</i>

04:06.279 --> 04:09.382
<i>from the normal garbage, but</i>

04:09.449 --> 04:11.951
<i>you read somewhere</i>
<i>that only 9% of plastic</i>

04:12.018 --> 04:14.387
<i>is actually recycled.</i>

04:15.722 --> 04:17.690
<i>And no matter how</i>
<i>environmentally conscious</i>

04:17.757 --> 04:19.292
<i>you think you're being,</i>

04:19.359 --> 04:21.794
<i>it feels like</i>
<i>it's just an illusion</i>

04:21.861 --> 04:24.530
<i>to ease your conscience.</i>

04:24.597 --> 04:26.633
♪ ♪

04:26.699 --> 04:29.035
<i>Maybe it's just</i>
<i>part of human nature</i>

04:29.102 --> 04:30.770
<i>to hope that something</i>

04:30.837 --> 04:32.505
<i>can take on another life</i>

04:32.572 --> 04:34.907
<i>and return in</i>
<i>a different form.</i>

04:34.974 --> 04:38.911
One thing that we see
in reincarnation cases

04:38.978 --> 04:41.981
is we're basically
the same person

04:42.048 --> 04:43.950
from lifetime to lifetime.

04:44.017 --> 04:48.187
The soul projects a hologram,

04:48.254 --> 04:51.124
if you will,
into the developing fetus,

04:51.190 --> 04:54.961
which results in
the facial features

04:55.028 --> 04:57.830
being similar from
lifetime to lifetime.

04:57.897 --> 05:01.100
Uh... Mark Zuckerberg

05:01.167 --> 05:04.937
was an early data programmer

05:05.004 --> 05:07.173
for the US Census.

05:07.240 --> 05:11.444
Uh, Jay Leno is
the reincarnation of Moliere.

05:11.511 --> 05:14.213
Michael Jackson, at age 10,

05:14.280 --> 05:16.416
was recruited into

05:16.482 --> 05:18.918
this children's army

05:18.985 --> 05:20.820
and was killed.

05:20.887 --> 05:23.756
The resemblance
is very striking.

05:23.823 --> 05:27.226
You know, the mouth
and the chin are
pretty much the same.

05:27.293 --> 05:29.262
-Wilson: Is that you?
-Reincarnation Man: Yep.

05:29.328 --> 05:31.297
-A few years back. (laughs)
-Wilson: You're saying

05:31.364 --> 05:33.633
you were the second President
of the United States?

05:33.700 --> 05:35.468
Reincarnation Man:
Correct.

05:35.535 --> 05:37.670
I met a woman,

05:37.737 --> 05:41.407
and within six months,
we were married.

05:42.108 --> 05:44.577
And it turned out that

05:44.644 --> 05:46.512
she was my son

05:46.579 --> 05:48.648
in the Adams lifetime.

05:48.715 --> 05:51.250
Wilson:
Wait, your wife was your--
the reincarnation

05:51.317 --> 05:54.454
-of your, John Adams' son?
-Yes.

05:54.520 --> 05:56.556
Wilson:
Is that, is that incest?

05:57.623 --> 06:00.660
Well, it's not incest because...

06:00.727 --> 06:02.428
they're different lifetimes.

06:02.495 --> 06:03.896
-Wilson: Oh, okay.
-Yeah.

06:03.963 --> 06:06.599
♪ ♪

06:06.666 --> 06:09.235
Wilson:
<i>When New Yorkers aren't sure</i>
<i>how to dispose of something,</i>

06:09.302 --> 06:12.305
<i>it usually ends up</i>
<i>on the sidewalk.</i>

06:12.371 --> 06:14.540
<i>They often place it</i>
<i>somewhere conspicuous</i>

06:14.607 --> 06:17.009
<i>in the hopes that</i>
<i>sanitation employees</i>

06:17.076 --> 06:19.112
<i>will remove it</i>
<i>because it's in the way.</i>

06:20.680 --> 06:22.181
<i>And law enforcement is</i>

06:22.248 --> 06:24.450
<i>absolutely powerless</i>
<i>to stop it.</i>

06:24.517 --> 06:25.651
(inaudible)

06:25.718 --> 06:27.854
<i>There's a safe that's</i>
<i>been on the sidewalk</i>

06:27.920 --> 06:30.323
<i>near my apartment</i>
<i>for a long time,</i>

06:30.389 --> 06:32.358
<i>and I have no idea</i>
<i>how it got there.</i>

06:32.425 --> 06:34.026
Do you know what's up
with this safe?

06:35.061 --> 06:36.229
Oh, okay.

06:37.463 --> 06:39.365
<i>It seems extremely</i>
<i>hard to move,</i>

06:39.432 --> 06:41.968
<i>and no matter how many</i>

06:42.034 --> 06:44.070
<i>of my favorite</i>
<i>combinations I try,</i>

06:44.137 --> 06:47.540
<i>I can't seem to get inside.</i>

06:47.607 --> 06:49.142
♪ ♪

06:49.208 --> 06:52.178
<i>City garbage cans are</i>
<i>also filled with objects</i>

06:52.245 --> 06:54.514
<i>that people aren't sure</i>
<i>how to throw out.</i>

06:54.580 --> 06:56.883
<i>But if you put</i>
<i>the wrong stuff in there,</i>

06:56.949 --> 07:00.019
<i>it can seriously damage</i>
<i>the people that collect it.</i>

07:00.086 --> 07:01.687
-How you doing, man?
Morning.
-Morning.

07:01.754 --> 07:04.123
People throw out steak knives

07:04.190 --> 07:07.093
in garbage bags.
Needles.

07:07.160 --> 07:08.694
That's the worst part.

07:08.761 --> 07:11.130
You pick up a bag,
and when it swings back...

07:11.197 --> 07:13.266
There was stitches.

07:13.332 --> 07:15.601
I cut the inside of my leg,

07:15.668 --> 07:17.703
and I think somewhere else.
Three times,

07:17.770 --> 07:20.373
-I wind up having to
get stitches on my leg.
-Wilson: Damn!

07:22.175 --> 07:24.210
Oh, look, look. Look! Here.

07:25.278 --> 07:26.813
-Wilson: What's that?
-Open it.

07:28.915 --> 07:31.951
-Wilson: Oh, shit.
-A guy in a garage
down the street

07:32.819 --> 07:34.453
had one of these explode on him,

07:34.520 --> 07:36.656
and he was in
the hospital for about...

07:36.722 --> 07:38.324
-What'd you say, about a month?
-Yeah.

07:38.391 --> 07:39.826
For about a month.

07:39.892 --> 07:42.028
-(whirring)
-(pop)

07:42.094 --> 07:43.963
There we go. Now,
if that was that tank,

07:44.030 --> 07:46.332
it's exploding on us.

07:46.399 --> 07:48.367
Know what
you're throwing out,
do your work.

07:48.434 --> 07:51.704
If you're not sure,
call 3-1-1.

07:51.771 --> 07:54.340
Wilson:
<i>It seems like if you throw</i>
<i>out something you shouldn't,</i>

07:54.407 --> 07:57.710
<i>they have to call in a special</i>
<i>waste department to handle it.</i>

07:57.777 --> 07:59.545
<i>And if you're sloppy,</i>

07:59.612 --> 08:01.647
<i>it could even go on</i>
<i>your permanent record.</i>

08:01.714 --> 08:03.316
Hazmat Worker:
Nine out of 10 times,
we will locate

08:03.382 --> 08:04.917
the individual
that deposited it,

08:04.984 --> 08:07.854
and if they're
found in violation,
we'll issue a violation.

08:07.920 --> 08:09.388
It could potentially
go criminal,

08:09.455 --> 08:12.425
-especially if someone's
severely injured.
-Wilson: Wow.

08:13.292 --> 08:15.995
<i>Once they took the tank away,</i>

08:16.062 --> 08:18.097
<i>you got to talking</i>
<i>with them a bit more,</i>

08:18.164 --> 08:20.399
<i>and you asked if</i>
<i>you could come see</i>

08:20.466 --> 08:23.102
<i>how the Department</i>
<i>of Sanitation works.</i>

08:23.169 --> 08:24.604
<i>And they actually said yeah.</i>

08:24.670 --> 08:26.138
♪ ♪

08:26.205 --> 08:29.642
<i>Everyone's garbage is</i>
<i>brought back to this facility</i>

08:29.709 --> 08:33.446
<i>and dumped into a big,</i>
<i>stinky pit by the dump trucks.</i>

08:35.014 --> 08:36.949
<i>And they have photos</i>
<i>of dangerous objects</i>

08:37.016 --> 08:38.384
<i>that they'll show you.</i>

08:38.451 --> 08:41.487
This is the remnants of
an oxygen tank that exploded.

08:41.554 --> 08:43.956
Shut down a two-block
radius in Manhattan.

08:44.023 --> 08:45.391
You can see
there's some syringes.

08:45.458 --> 08:48.728
You have some acid,
poison, arsenic.

08:48.794 --> 08:52.498
Just a simple photograph
of our offices.

08:52.565 --> 08:56.302
Wilson:
<i>Then they let you go to the</i>
<i>recycling facility next door,</i>

08:56.369 --> 08:59.472
<i>where they have people</i>
<i>separating things by hand.</i>

08:59.538 --> 09:01.774
<i>And they take a second to</i>
<i>tell you how dangerous it is</i>

09:01.841 --> 09:04.277
<i>to have batteries mixed in</i>
<i>with the recycling.</i>

09:04.343 --> 09:06.879
So, musical greeting cards,
for example, um,

09:06.946 --> 09:09.115
you don't think about it,
but there's a battery in there.

09:09.181 --> 09:11.884
And there is actually
a fire in New Jersey,

09:11.951 --> 09:13.619
there's a paper
recycling facility,

09:13.686 --> 09:16.255
and the entire facility
burned to the ground.

09:16.322 --> 09:18.257
So, here's an example
of a battery.

09:18.324 --> 09:20.726
This is an e-bike battery.
It came into our facility.

09:20.793 --> 09:22.895
We didn't actually
ask for this,

09:22.962 --> 09:24.664
but someone thought
they should be recycled.

09:24.730 --> 09:26.132
And it could create
a smoldering condition,

09:26.198 --> 09:27.833
and it's hugely dangerous.

09:27.900 --> 09:29.468
-We're good!
-Worker: Alright, no problem.

09:31.637 --> 09:32.972
Wilson:
Um...

09:33.039 --> 09:36.442
<i>The tour was</i>
<i>really eye-opening,</i>
<i>and you didn't realize</i>

09:36.509 --> 09:38.711
<i>that such a gentle</i>
<i>household object</i>

09:38.778 --> 09:42.281
<i>could be responsible</i>
<i>for so much devastation.</i>

09:42.348 --> 09:45.351
(dogs barking
"Happy Birthday")

09:47.787 --> 09:50.556
<i>When you look on YouTube, you</i>
<i>see that there's actually a guy</i>

09:50.623 --> 09:52.491
<i>who's dedicated</i>
<i>his entire life</i>

09:52.558 --> 09:55.227
<i>to warning people</i>
<i>about stuff like this.</i>

09:55.294 --> 09:57.596
This chainsaw may
unexpectedly start

09:57.663 --> 09:59.332
without pressing
the power switch

09:59.398 --> 10:02.501
when the extension cord adapter
is connected upside down.

10:02.568 --> 10:05.104
These pastries
may contain mold.

10:05.171 --> 10:08.307
If you bought the carrots, don't
consume them, but destroy them.

10:08.374 --> 10:11.277
These garments failed to meet
federal flammability standards

10:11.344 --> 10:12.545
for children's sleepwear,

10:12.611 --> 10:15.982
and they create a risk
for childhood burn injuries.

10:16.048 --> 10:18.617
Do not permit your child
to wear these nightgowns.

10:18.684 --> 10:22.521
Contact La Paloma
and arrange a refund.

10:22.588 --> 10:23.856
Wilson:
Nightgowns are flammable?

10:23.923 --> 10:27.193
Yep. Well, they're supposed
to be not be flammable.

10:27.259 --> 10:28.728
-Wilson: Oh, right, right.
-But, they are.

10:28.794 --> 10:31.497
Wilson:
Why do you think people
hold on to recalled products

10:31.564 --> 10:33.966
even if they know they've--
they're dangerous?

10:34.033 --> 10:36.369
Well, most people
collect any product

10:36.435 --> 10:38.871
because they think
it is a collector's item.

10:38.938 --> 10:40.506
That is, it's valuable.

10:40.573 --> 10:42.575
So, I imagine
if you had a bottle,

10:42.641 --> 10:45.411
a jar with something in it,

10:45.478 --> 10:48.481
like a screw or a bolt or a nut,

10:48.547 --> 10:52.251
that probably would be
an interesting collector's item.

10:52.318 --> 10:54.754
Wilson:
<i>You never really thought</i>
<i>of it like that before.</i>

10:54.820 --> 10:56.989
<i>That something you</i>
<i>thought was defective</i>

10:57.056 --> 11:00.593
<i>could actually become</i>
<i>a collectible one day.</i>

11:00.659 --> 11:02.261
♪ ♪

11:02.328 --> 11:04.296
<i>Maybe if we just</i>
<i>take care of objects</i>

11:04.363 --> 11:06.399
<i>that nobody else wants,</i>

11:06.465 --> 11:09.835
<i>they might actually</i>
<i>end up in a museum.</i>

11:09.902 --> 11:12.638
<i>And there could</i>
<i>even be hidden value</i>

11:12.705 --> 11:13.973
<i>inside of your stuff</i>

11:14.040 --> 11:15.808
<i>if you could just learn</i>

11:15.875 --> 11:18.177
<i>how to crack the code.</i>

